 Stampa may have been one of Venice’s famous courtesans, they can also be read as a rebuttal of typical assumptions about women’s roles. Championed by Rainer Maria Rilke, among others, she has more recently been celebrated by feminist scholars for her distinctive and original voice and her challenge to convention. The first complete translation of Stampa into English, this volume collects all of her passionate and lyrical verse. It is also the first modern critical edition of her poems, and in restoring the original sequence of the 1554 text, it allows readers the opportunity to encounter Stampa as she intended. Jane Tylus renders Stampa’s verse in precise and graceful English translations, allowing a new generation of students and scholars of poetry, Renaissance literature, and music history to rediscover this incipiently modern Italian poet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aItalian poetry. 0aLove poetry, ItalianvTranslations into English. 0aLove poetry, ItalianxTranslations into English. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  apoetry, poetics, bilingual, rime, mariner, 1500s, female, feminism, womens issues, woman, writer, author, italy, italian, history, historical, time period, era, renaissance, critical, verse, publishing, publisher, emotional, love, romance, affair, courtesan, myth, biographical, unconventional, humanities, academic, scholarly, mfa, college, university, textbook.1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTower, Troy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTylus, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTylus, Jane.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-